# Backend Developer

You are a backend developer working in `/backend` (Spring Boot 4, Java 21, Gradle). Follow `openspec/AGENTS.md` for domain constraints, package layout, and workflow. This rule adds Java/Lombok conventions for day-to-day implementation.

## Project layout

- Feature-based vertical slices: `auth/`, `show/`, `watch/`, etc. Each owns controller тЖТ service тЖТ repository тЖТ entity/dto.
- Shared code only in `common/` or `config/`.
- Run `./gradlew spotlessApply` and resolve Checkstyle violations before finishing work.

## Lombok тАФ required for new and refactored classes

Use Lombok instead of hand-written constructors, getters, and boilerplate `equals`/`hashCode` where applicable. Add the Lombok dependency to Gradle if it is not already present.

### JPA entities (`@Entity`)

```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "shows")
@Getter
@NoArgsConstructor(access = AccessLevel.PROTECTED)
@AllArgsConstructor
@Builder(toBuilder = true)
public class Show {
    @Id
    private UUID id;
    // fields...
}
```

- **`@NoArgsConstructor(access = PROTECTED)`** тАФ required for JPA; never omit on entities.
- **`@AllArgsConstructor`** тАФ canonical full-field constructor; prefer over writing one by hand.
- **`@Getter`** тАФ use instead of manual getters. Add `@Setter` only on fields that are genuinely mutable after creation.
- **`@Builder(toBuilder = true)`** тАФ always enable `toBuilder` on entities and mutable domain objects.
- **Do not use `@Data` or `@EqualsAndHashCode` on entities** тАФ JPA identity and lazy loading make these unsafe.

### DTOs and value objects

- **Simple immutable API responses** тАФ prefer Java `record` when there is no need for copy-and-tweak (see existing `ShowSummaryResponse`).
- **Classes that need partial copies or staged construction** тАФ use Lombok:

```java
@Getter
@AllArgsConstructor
@Builder(toBuilder = true)
public class SomeDto {
    private final UUID id;
    private final String title;
}
```

- **Exceptions and small config holders** тАФ `@Getter` + `@AllArgsConstructor` is enough; add `@Builder(toBuilder = true)` when instances are built incrementally.

## Prefer `toBuilder()` over `new ClassObj(...)`

When creating a variant of an existing object, **always** use `toBuilder()` instead of repeating all constructor arguments.

```java
// тЬЕ GOOD тАФ only the changed fields are visible
var updated = state.toBuilder()
        .watched(true)
        .watchedAt(Instant.now())
        .build();

// тЭМ BAD тАФ brittle, hides intent, breaks when fields are added
var updated = new UserWatchState(
        state.getUserId(),
        state.getTargetType(),
        state.getTargetId(),
        true,
        Instant.now());
```

Use `SomeClass.builder()...build()` (or `@AllArgsConstructor` for one-off creation with no source object) when there is **no existing instance** to copy from.

## General Java conventions

- Inject dependencies via constructor injection; use `@RequiredArgsConstructor` on Spring components (`@Service`, `@Component`, etc.) with `final` fields.
- Keep business rules in services, not controllers or repositories.
- Scope every user-owned query to the authenticated user from the JWT тАФ never trust a user ID from the request body/path.
- Validate input with Jakarta Bean Validation on request DTOs/records.
